  <info><![CDATA[
# Hormuz Escalation ABM (v1.88, Conference)

Author: Young Joon Oh

A hybrid agent-based model of a maritime-chokepoint crisis at the Strait of Hormuz. Rule-based strategic agents (United States, Iran, Israel) interact with aggregate adaptive submodels for commercial insurance, the oil market, and diplomacy. Each layer recovers from a shock at its own speed, governed by four clocks with recovery rates r_M (military, fixed at 1.0 as the baseline), r_C (commercial), r_K (oil market), and r_D (diplomatic).

## Focal outcome
Managed stalemate: military violence has paused but commercial and market activity have not normalized. The run-level measure is whether a run ever displays the signature (a military pause with elevated war-risk premium, depressed access, and no formal ceasefire).

## How to run
1. Set the sliders. The main lever is the commercial-clock rate (tau-c-rate, written r_C in the paper); a value below 1.0 is a slow commercial clock.
2. Click `setup`, then `go`.
3. Batch experiments are in BehaviorSpace (Tools > BehaviorSpace).

## Verify the parameter surface
python extract_literals.py Hormuz_Escalation_ver_1_88_conference.nlogox --out ./scan

## Documentation
Full ODD and TRACE documentation, the decision lineage, and all results are in the companion paper and its supplements (Oh 2026).

]]></info>
